         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">21/7/65. ¶ Dear Sir William. ¶  ¶ I was delighted to hear from your worthy son, that you are restored to health ¶  May it please providence to grant it to you long yet and unimpaired. What is to all o...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">65.07.21a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, f. 170.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">21/7/65.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dear Sir William.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was delighted to hear from your worthy son, that you are restored to health<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See J. Hooker to M, 19 May 1865.</p>
               </note> May it please providence to grant it to you long yet and unimpaired. What is to all of us dear, your valued life, I trust you will guard to the utmost. May you long guide us all then not merely by your works but also still with your living extraordinar[y] example.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am aware you take a profound continued interest in ferns. So let me say a few words about them. I had occasion to examine recently the fern trees of the garden. On the occasion I revised all the Australian species, and as you returned the Alsophilae undetermined &amp; doubtful as regards their limits, I have ventured to draw up diagnoses of the two southern species, which I find very &amp; constantly distinct. A third from the N.E. coast is very similar. But 2 others from Rockingham's Bay<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Qld.</p>
               </note> are remarkably different from all even the extraaustralian kinds. <name key="Alsophila%20Rebeccae">Alsophila Rebeccae</name>, named in honor of a lovely young Ladyfriend of mine,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Rebecca Nordt, a member of the Ladies' Leichhardt Committee. See Brown-May &amp; Maroske (1994) for the circumstances of the naming.</p>
               </note> is a truely graceful plant, the stem only 1'' diameter by 6' high. I will send living plants to Kew. <name key="Alsophila%20Robertsiana">Alsophila Robertsiana</name> is, if we look at the fronds merely, bearing much resemblance to <name key="Hypolepis%20tenuifolia">Hypolepis tenuifolia</name> &amp; <name key="Polypodium%20rugosulum">Polypodium rugosulum</name>.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>rugulosum?</p>
               </note> — So with <name key="Cyatheae">Cyatheae</name> &amp; <name key="Osmunda">Osmunda</name> we know now 8 treeferns in Australia; RBr had 3; - and it is not unlikely that future researches in the jungles of N.E. Australia (but only there) will add to the number. Whenever your synopsis will be completed,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hooker and Baker (1868)</p>
               </note> I shall, if I live, draw up a special little publication on all the ferns of Australia, there being here like at home a predilection manifested for this tribe of plants.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever with profound regards your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I have to express my thanks for the handsome manner in which you referred to my contributions in your report.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In his Report for 1864, dated 1 January 1865, Hooker did not treat M differently from others named, but listed him as a contributor to the Botanic Gardens, the Arboretum and Winter Garden, and the Herbarium and Library.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
